Investigating Bus Suspects: A Journey Through Delays & Crowds

Lets set the stage: What’s our Problem?

Every day, many of us rely on public transport and experience varying trip lengths, delays, and crowds. But what causes these problems? Why do they emerge? When we log and analyze this information systematically are we able to find out patterns that may help us in the future? Using a dataset of bus trip logs, let’s explore how time of day, day of the week, and trip characteristics impact the rider experience. Please be seated or holding the rail bars at all times!

We can start to examine how trip durations vary depending on the time of day and whether it’s a weekday or weekend. The density plot above reveals noticeable differences in bus trip lengths throughout the day.

We can see that there is a lot more variability in bus trip duration during weekdays compared to weekends. When we look at the weekday side first, the only time of day that is not so variable is the Night. We can see that there is pretty high probability that bus duration will be around 20 minutes, which is much lower compared to buses taken during the morning, afternoon and evening. This is most likely due to the fact that buses are much less crowded during the night, and peak hours are during the morning and afternoon period(for university students, for full-time working adults, the evening more of a rush hour than the afternoon).

On the weekend side we see that there is a very high probability that bus duration is highly likely to be 30 minutes in the evening, and during the morning we see two peaks(one at approx. 32 minutes and lower peak at approx. 24 minutes). This shows that on average bus trips I’ve taken during the weekends have been relatively shorter than during the weekdays, and there are to be much more unexpected differences in trip duration.

I think these results can help me identify what the best times are to take public transport when I have a choice. In my case, it seems that night buses result in the shortest bus durations, so I could potentially wait/study at Uni until night to avoid traffic or delays when possible.

Quantifying Delay With An Intelligent Twist?

Our above box plot examines how trip lengths vary depending on the time of day and whether it’s a weekday or weekend. The density plot below reveals noticeable differences in bus trip lengths throughout the day.

This is a similar relationship to our density plot, but here we have tried to calculate a way to normalise delay. So I kind of pulled this concept from CS110 when we learnt about artificial neurons. To make the comparison fair, I made my own metric: delay_score = bus_duration / (distance_factor x crowdedness_factor).

The idea was to account for trip complexity, as longer trips should naturally take longer, and crowded buses should move more slowly. This isn’t an official formula, but more of a prototype inspired by how weights are handled in artificial neurons (thanks, CS110!).

Now lets get on with the results from the plot. As we can see, 2 zones has by far the highest delay score, in comparison to 1 zone and 3 zones. Which is to be expected, as longer journeys essentially are more likely to introduce some random event that may cause delay. I dont think we have enough data for 3 zones to make any assumptions yet, but I guess we could say it may have a similar delay score compared to 2 zone trips.

Crowd Levels Be Like: Mood Swings on Wheels!

In the bar chart above we explore how crowdedness(on a scale of 1-5) varies across different parts of the day, separating weekdays from weekends.

The results are actually quite interesting, as we see similar and higher peaks from morning and afternoon (score ~4) time of day during the weekdays compared to the evenings. This might due to bias of the population as I(uni student) mostly finish uni either before the evening or at night and I’m presuming this might be similar to most students schedules, hence the most crowded period time of day are usually Mornings and Afternoons(potentially closer to 3pm as opposed to noon).

However, weekends remain less crowded overall (scores 1-2) with slightly higher activity in afternoons. Nights consistently show the lowest crowdedness across all days. The data suggests weekdays face significant rush-hour pressure, whereas weekend travel demand is more relaxed, probably due to flexible schedules and reduced work-related trips, and many university who catch the same bus as me might relax at home during this period.

Mastering Tetris on a Moving Bus

This stacked bar chart shows how crowdedness severity (High vs. Low) varies across trip durations (Short/Medium/Long). Our main insights from this chart is:

  • Long trips have the highest proportion of “High” crowdedness, suggesting buses on extended routes are consistently packed, but this is only by slightly.
  • Short trips show slightly less “Low” crowdedness than Long trips, likely because people get off and on frequently, which likely prevents sustained crowding.
  • And, medium-length trips show the lowest crowdedness severity. This was weird, because I predicted medium length trips and long trips to have similar severity in terms of crowding but it seems like I was quite wrong.

Exposing Buses who are chronically late…

Finally for our last plot, we can expose some bus numbers. This plot compares delay scores (a metric combining duration, distance, and crowdedness) across different bus routes.

From my collected data, we find evidence that the 70/72X stands out for having both the highest average delay and the largest spread of individual delay scores. This suggests that not only are delays more frequent or severe for this route, but there’s also higher variability, indicating a lack of reliability in its schedule(as usual for the 70 :( ). This is likely because the 70 bus is so popular and pretty travel throughout the North Island(I’m exaggerating) making it so convenient for most Uni students.

Whereas, the 27H/T/W bus has the lowest average delay score, with individual scores tightly clustered near the bottom of the y-axis. This shows more consistent and timings and less delays on this route. I think its because there are 3 different buses that essentially run on the same route and they are so frequent that It makes it very hard the bus to be late or delayed, and allows for less crowding.

The other bus lines(24B, 25B/L, and 321) show average delays that fall between the extremes of 27H/T/W and 70/72X. Their mean scores hover slightly below the 70/72x’s delay score, suggesting moderate-bad delays. Among all the buses, 24B and 25B/L are particularly similar, with nearly identical average scores and relatively low variation among their individual delay score. This might be because these bs routes are not as popular as some of the others, hence why even though they might not be delayed, they are still slightly infrequent which may cause a build up of crowds.
